<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="108" pageId="4" pageNumber="107" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1420,2024]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,358]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="108" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,517,1420,1447]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">
Description. MALE. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[455,517,1420,1447]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Head</emphasis>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[535,656,1421,1447]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1959,1983]" captionTargetBox="[164,1411,205,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[164,1424,181,1936]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A, C, D male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. B, E male of Cheilosia paralobi. A, B head, lateral view, C head, dorsal view, D, E antennae, lateral view. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402962/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Figs 1A, 1</figureCitation>
C–D). Antennae dark, brown-reddish; basoflagellomere dark-brown with reddish macula basoventrally, ellipsoidal, about 1.3 times as long as broad, and 3.5 longer than pedicel; arista 1.5 times longer than antennae, covered with short pile (
<figureCitation box="[797,887,1493,1519]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1959,1983]" captionTargetBox="[164,1411,205,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[164,1424,181,1936]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A, C, D male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. B, E male of Cheilosia paralobi. A, B head, lateral view, C head, dorsal view, D, E antennae, lateral view. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402962/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
); face wide, 1/2 of the width of head anteriorly, covered with long, pale-yellow pile along paraface in upper 1/3 (
<figureCitation box="[881,970,1529,1555]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1959,1983]" captionTargetBox="[164,1411,205,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[164,1424,181,1936]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A, C, D male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. B, E male of Cheilosia paralobi. A, B head, lateral view, C head, dorsal view, D, E antennae, lateral view. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402962/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
); facial tubercle rounded; genae, face between antennae and facial tubercle, and along paraface covered with grey microtrichia; frons convex, shiny, covered with mixed yellow and black pile; vertex convex and shiny; ocellar triangle equilateral, covered with mixed yellow and black pile; eyes bare; eye contiguity shorter than length of frons (
<figureCitation box="[925,1011,1637,1663]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1959,1983]" captionTargetBox="[164,1411,205,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[164,1424,181,1936]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A, C, D male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. B, E male of Cheilosia paralobi. A, B head, lateral view, C head, dorsal view, D, E antennae, lateral view. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402962" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402962/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
); occiput narrow, with white-grey microtrichia, covered with yellow pile, with additional black pile dorsally along eye margin. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1160,1246,1672,1699]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Thorax</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1261,1329,1673,1699]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1647,1671]" captionTargetBox="[167,1424,396,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-90@5.[153,1434,381,1623]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. A thorax, lateral view B metafemur and metatibia, lateral view C body, dorsal view. Scale bar, A, B 0.5 mm, C 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402966/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Scutum black, with dark-golden color, laterally slightly microtrichose, covered with long yellow pile, except wing bases covered with black pile and few black ones in notopleural area; central disk shiny, with fine punctuation; scutellum covered with yellow pile (
<figureCitation box="[448,572,1781,1807]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1647,1671]" captionTargetBox="[167,1424,396,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-90@5.[153,1434,381,1623]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. A thorax, lateral view B metafemur and metatibia, lateral view C body, dorsal view. Scale bar, A, B 0.5 mm, C 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402966/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 3A, C</figureCitation>
); metathoracic pleuron slightly microtrichose, covered with pale-yellow pile and wavy at apical end; wing membrane brownish medially, with brown veins, completely microtrichose; vein M1 meeting vein R4+5 at acute angle; halters light to dark-brown; calypteres yellowish-gray; all legs dark-brown/black, except light-brown apex of femora, basal 1/3 and apical end of tibiae, and ventral surface of tarsi; legs grey microtrichose and with mixed yellow and black pile, although yellow ones dominate (
<figureCitation box="[1036,1123,1925,1951]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1647,1671]" captionTargetBox="[167,1424,396,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-90@5.[153,1434,381,1623]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. A thorax, lateral view B metafemur and metatibia, lateral view C body, dorsal view. Scale bar, A, B 0.5 mm, C 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402966/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1143,1253,1924,1951]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1268,1355,1925,1951]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1647,1671]" captionTargetBox="[167,1424,396,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-90@5.[153,1434,381,1623]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Cheilosia candida sp. n. A thorax, lateral view B metafemur and metatibia, lateral view C body, dorsal view. Scale bar, A, B 0.5 mm, C 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402966/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Terga dull, covered with mostly yellow pile, except few black ones on pregenital segment; sterna grey microtrichose, covered with yellow pile, except few black ones on sternum 4. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[859,1026,1996,2023]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1042,1111,1997,2023]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[155,1434,937,1700]" captionTargetId="figure-1497@6.[151,1436,931,1704]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia of Cheilosia candida sp. n., lateral view. A male genitalia without surstylus B surstylus. ep—epandrium, hp—hypandrium, ce—cercus, godl—dorsal lobus of gonostylus, arrow pointed dorsal prolongation on godl, govl—ventral lobus of gonostylus. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402968" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402968/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Surstylus about three times longer than broad basally, with central bulge from lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[865,954,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[155,1434,937,1700]" captionTargetId="figure-1497@6.[151,1436,931,1704]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia of Cheilosia candida sp. n., lateral view. A male genitalia without surstylus B surstylus. ep—epandrium, hp—hypandrium, ce—cercus, godl—dorsal lobus of gonostylus, arrow pointed dorsal prolongation on godl, govl—ventral lobus of gonostylus. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402968" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402968/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
); dorsal lobus of gonostylus sickle-shaped, with spine-like dorsal prolongation (marked with arrow on 
<figureCitation box="[815,905,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[155,1434,937,1700]" captionTargetId="figure-1497@6.[151,1436,931,1704]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia of Cheilosia candida sp. n., lateral view. A male genitalia without surstylus B surstylus. ep—epandrium, hp—hypandrium, ce—cercus, godl—dorsal lobus of gonostylus, arrow pointed dorsal prolongation on godl, govl—ventral lobus of gonostylus. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402968" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402968/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,358]" box="[199,451,222,249]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,222,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">FEMALE.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="108" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,358]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,259,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named according to the Latin adjective ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Radenković &amp; Likov &amp; Ståhls &amp; Rojo &amp; Pérez-Bañón &amp; Smit &amp; Petanidou &amp; Steenis &amp; Vujić" authorityYear="2020" box="[1030,1120,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="candida">
<emphasis box="[1030,1120,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">candida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ meaning bright (not dark), indicating yellow color of body pile and reddish antennae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1168,330,358]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,358]" box="[199,1168,330,358]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,330,356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[567,649,331,357]" name="Greece" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Greece</collectingCountry>
, from a locality on Pindos Mountains (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1154,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1103,1127]" captionTargetBox="[176,1411,181,1076]" captionTargetId="figure-25@8.[176,1411,181,1080]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution map of newly described species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402972" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402972/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
